Description: State of the art prosthetics and a revolutionary socket design that allows rapid donning and doffing without losing strength
Headquarters Regions: Greater Denver Area, Western US
Full Description: Quorum Prosthetics has been in business for over 21 years and provides services to over 4,000 customers a year. With three locations in northern Colorado and southern Wyoming, including a manufacturing facility in Windsor, Colorado, Quorum is the premier prosthetic manufacturer and treatment center for the region. The company sees over $3 million a year in revenue.  The company provides for a wide variety of customers, ranging from amputees requiring full prosthetics to people in need of orthotics. As an all inclusive provider, Quorum is able to make all the products in-house while also providing for the customer’s needs including consultations, measurements, and physical therapy.  Quorum services many customers with above the knee and elbow amputations. These clients require a specialized approach in order to be able to move naturally and comfortably. Quorum invests time and effort into researching the most effective approaches to these types of prosthetics. Joe Johnson, the co-owner/CEO of the company, holds one patent and has another five pending for products that may revolutionize the current approach for these customers. The full patent is for a product called “The Quatro.” The Quatro is a revolutionary new design that will allow a user to have additional adjustability, comfort, performance, and efficiency that is not available with existing sockets. It is the only device on the market that allows three zones of compression, all easily adjusted through BOA RevoFit™ dials. Best of all, it can fit on any user’s existing socket, helping to save the user costs and add flexibility while increasing Quorum’s customer base. While the Quatro can be used with most any design, Quorum has chosen to partner with Biodesigns to utilize the highly effective HiFi socket for the prototypes. The HiFi system offers a high level of intrinsic bone control as the interface captures and reproduces skeletal motion. The system has been proven to decrease hip abduction by 14 degrees, increase hip extension 13 degrees, and provide less circumduction, allowing the subject to feel more stable. When these aspects come together, the HiFi socket provides the patient increased proprioception and prosthetic control and the ability to walk faster with a more symmetrical gait. Due to this compression, the HiFi is excellent at capturing and stabilizing a residual bone. However, the same technology makes it tougher for many patients to don the socket as they are typically swollen in the morning. Through research, it was also discovered that a residual limb can fluctuate up to 8.5% throughout an 8 hour period. This can be due to factors such as heat, water loss/gain, or aggravation. The HiFi system is also incapable of adjusting for this fluctuation.  Quorum developed a solution to these drawbacks. The Quatro offers three independently adjustable zones, which allow fluctuations as high as 10% while also providing 60 pounds of compression. The wearer can modify the compression and overall size by simply adjusting one of the three knobs located on the socket. Quorum chose to utilize BOA dials for changing compression because they allow for easy adjustments and rapid donning and doffing. Current technologies do not allow this level of freedom and comfort and many users resort to padding their socket with socks or other materials to adjust for fluctuation and comfort. The partnerships not only provide great materials for this design, but they will help the company scale operations as it introduces the Quatro to market. The design fits on almost any existing socket, allowing Quatro to work with most companies, including their existing agreement with Biodesigns. Also, with an investment in new technologies, Quorum will be able to receive scans of patients limbs from any practitioner in the world and produce a custom designed Quatro for anyone, regardless of proximity.

Full Description: Coaching adds more joy to life!  You can FIND JOY in the chaos of your life. In this serious business of joy you will be inspired to understand yourself, find direction, and develop habits that bring clarity, energy, and satisfaction to both business and personal life. I am divorced and a single mother of three "almost grown" children. My divorce, while the most painful experience of my life, has brought me new skills, confidence, and an overwhelming desire to coach women and men, both single and married, to live an abundant life. My clients learn how to live with gratitude, focus, and peace that cannot be shaken by troubling circumstances that life sometimes brings. Divorce and parenting challenges are my main passion for coaching. I've studied them, written about them, and lived them! Relationships are key to fulfillment in life and when relationships are missing or broken, we struggle to find joy. The coaching help available through Find Joy, especially one-on-one life coaching, has changed my clients' lives. If you're feeling overwhelmed, low, or exhausted we can Find Joy together! Credentials:   Life Coach — As a Life Coach, trained through the accredited Institute for Life Coach Training, I am able to fulfill my life purpose statement, "I creatively inspire people to understand themselves and find direction for their lives." Certified Family Life Educator — I've spent 25 years learning and teaching about child development, parent-teen relationships, parenting styles, and family dynamics. Parenting Author — Along with my co-author, Janice Rubin, I've written two parenting books for use in small groups. Let's Talk Parenting: 10 Bible Characters Every Family Should Meet and Let's Talk Teens: 10 Questions to Connect Parents, Teens, and God have been used by churches of nearly every Christian denomination. Janice and I are also the founders of Family Impact, Inc., a business created to bring families closer together and closer to God. Adult Education Specialist — I have a passion for understanding what motivates adults to build relationships and change behaviors. The amount we learn is directly proportionate to the amount of fun we're having, and so my presentations are challenging, personal, and motivational — but never boring!

Description: American College of Cardiology, Society of Thoracic Surgeons certified databases and related products.
Headquarters Regions: Southern US
Full Description: Medical Dynamics has been around for awhile.  Their first Inventory and QA system began in 1984.  At that time Cardiac Imaging used “Cine Film” to record the Cath Lab images.  High speed cameras exposed long reels of cine film at frame rates up to 60 frames per second.  Most recordings were 30 frames per second which showed enough detail.  Many pediatric cath labs used 60 frames giving a more precise recording of  those rapidly beating very small hearts.  The film, after exposure, was placed in a “processor” and developed before viewing on projectors.  This method had potential for quality problems ranging from film batch differences, processor parameters mal-adjusted, and exposure/camera problems.  However, this was the only game in town for recording images reliably and at high resolution.  The other options included video tape recordings and early hard drive recorders.  These methods typically did not match the resolution and clarity of film until the late 1990s.

Description: Java search engine
Headquarters Regions: Greater Los Angeles Area, West Coast, Western US
Full Description: Jarvana is a search engine for millions of Java classes, projects, and content in the maven central repository that allows Java developers to find Java classes, their associated jar files, source code, documentation, and maven dependency information. Java developers can use Jarvana to search for classes to resolve NoClassDefFoundError and ClassNotFoundException issues. Search results include detailed information about Java classes and archive files such as jar files. If available, relevant source code and javadocs for classes can be viewed online. An explorer-like maven repository browser provides useful functionality such as sorting and detailed information about maven repository directory and archive contents. Users can drill into archive files (.jar, .zip, .tar.gz, etc.) and inspect the contents of archives via the web interface. Jarvana is particularly useful for Java developers who use the Apache Maven project management and build tool.  Developers who use maven can utilize Jarvana to obtain maven dependency information for classes and artifacts, inspect POM files, and inspect maven plugins. Jarvana helps Java developers work more efficiently since developers can find relevant information quickly and easily using this web-based search application.
